# API Contracts

- The API is the primary contract for React, Android, and future integrations. Do not create client-specific business behavior.
- Public business routes start with `/api/v1`.
- Endpoints stay thin: bind input, call application logic, and map results to standard HTTP responses.
- Request and response DTOs must be explicit and stable. Do not leak EF entities or internal strongly typed IDs.
- Single-item responses return the DTO directly. List endpoints return `PagedResult<T>`.
- Create endpoints return `201 Created` with the created DTO or created id.
- Update endpoints return `204 No Content` unless the UI truly needs the updated DTO.
- Delete, deactivate, and archive endpoints return `204 No Content`.
- List endpoints use server-side pagination with 1-based `page`, default `pageSize` of 20, and maximum `pageSize` of 100 unless documented otherwise.
- Filtering uses explicit typed query parameters. Avoid OData and generic dynamic query languages for v1.0.0.
- Sorting uses `field:direction`, for example `name:asc` or `createdAt:desc`.
- Use consistent ProblemDetails responses: validation 400, auth 401, authorization 403, missing resources 404, business conflicts 409, unexpected exceptions 500.
- ProblemDetails should include `type`, `title`, `status`, `detail`, `instance`, `traceId`, and an application error code when available.
- Use permission-based authorization. Avoid role-only checks.
- Permission names use lowercase dot format, for example `core.manpower-types.view` or `operations.work-orders.approve`.
- Breaking API changes require explicit review because Android and React share the same contract.
- Use optimistic concurrency on update endpoints via ETag/`If-Match`. Return 409 on a concurrency conflict.
- Support idempotency keys on create/mutating endpoints so retrying mobile clients do not create duplicates.
- Exchange time in UTC ISO-8601. Honor `Accept-Language` (Arabic/English) for localized validation and error messages.
- Apply rate limiting to authentication and other abuse-prone public endpoints.
- Treat OpenAPI as a first-class artifact. Generated clients/types should be reproducible and should not be hand-edited.
